{{infobox Organization |name = ESA Centre for Earth Observation |image = ESA ESRIN Vega.jpg |image_border = |size = 250px |caption = Inside the ESA Centre for Earth Observation, with a Vega rocket model |abbreviation = ESRIN |motto = |formation = |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = |location = [[Frascati]], [[Italy]] |region_served = |membership = |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = [[European Space Agency]] |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{url|http://www.esa.int/About_Us/ESRIN}} |remarks = }}
{{Coord|41.8269472|12.6741222|type:landmark_region:IT|format=dms|display=title}}
The '''ESA Centre for Earth Observation''' (also known as the '''European Space Research Institute''' or '''ESRIN''') is a research centre belonging to the [[European Space Agency]] (ESA), located in [[Frascati]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.satellite-links.co.uk/directory/european-space-research-institute-esrin.html|title=European Space Research Institute (ESRIN)|publisher=Satellite Industry Links|accessdate=10 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924094411/http://www.satellite-links.co.uk/directory/european-space-research-institute-esrin.html|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=}}</ref> It is dedicated to research involving [[earth observation]] data taken from satellites, among other specialised activities. The establishment currently hosts the European Space Agency's development team for the [[Vega (rocket)|Vega launcher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/About_Us/ESRIN/Vega_launcher|title=Vega Launcher|publisher=[[ESA]]|date=1 September 2005|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>
==History== ESLAR, a laboratory for advanced research was created in 1966 mainly to break the political deadlock over the location of [[ESLAB]]. Later renamed ESRIN, an acronym for European Space Research Institute, ESLAR was based in Frascati (Italy).<ref name="46yearsESRIN">{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/About_Us/Welcome_to_ESA/ESA_history/ESRIN_foundation_46_years_ago|title=ESRIN foundation 46 years ago|publisher=[[ESA]]|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> The [[ESRO]] Convention describes ESRINs' role in the following manner: {{Quotation| ...to undertake laboratory and theoretical research in the basic physics and chemistry necessary to the understanding of past and the planning of future experiments in space.|ESRO Convention<ref name="46yearsESRIN"/>}} The facility began acquiring data from environmental satellites within [[Earthnet programme]] in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/esapub/bulletin/bullet99/franc99.pdf|title=ESRIN – Its Development and Role|format=PDF|publisher=[[ESA]]|first1=Roberto|last1=Franciosi|date=September 1999|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>
==See also== * [[European Space Operations Centre]] (ESOC) * [[European Space Research and Technology Centre]] (ESTEC) * [[European Space Astronomy Centre]] (ESAC) * [[European Astronaut Centre]] (EAC) * [[European Centre for Space Applications and Telecommunications]] (ECSAT) * [[Guiana Space Centre]] (CSG) * [[ESTRACK|European Space Tracking Network]] (ESTRACK) * [[European Space Agency]] (ESA)
