'''Lehel''' is the name of the largest [[Hungary|Hungarian]] appliance company.<ref Name="Fallon&Bedford">{{cite book |title= Hungary |last= Fallon & Bedford |first= |authorlink= |author2=Steve Fallon |author3=Neal Bedford |year=2003 |publisher=Lonely Planet |location= |isbn=1-74059-152-6 |page= 286 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FfkOpHEUGA0C&pg=PA269&dq=Lehel+%28appliances%29&hl=en&ei=iFUDTbSnG4SClAes-YnaCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Lehel%20%28appliances%29&f=false }}</ref> The company was owned by the state during the [[socialist]] era (1945–1989), and was mostly known for its [[refrigerators]], which were in widespread use. After two years of negotiations, the company was acquired by [[Electrolux]] for [[US$]]83 million in 1991.<ref> {{cite web |title=1988–1999 Privatization Transaction Data |publisher=World Bank Group |year=2000 |url=http://www.fdi.net/documents/WorldBank/databases/plink/soceco/1hungary.htm |accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref> At the time of the acquisition, Lehel had about 5,000 employees and was considered one of the best functioning companies in Hungary.<ref>{{cite book |title=East-West Business Relations: Establishment and Development |first=Jarmo |last=Nieminen |publisher=International Business Press |location=Binghampton, NY |isbn=1-56024-747-9 |year=1996 |page=9 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=cmri0LcYBxIC}}</ref>
